As for mob movement, depends on the camp I guess. On the wall camps in Valor Castle, if you are pulling along the wall it doesnt really matter if the mobs shift a few feet during the fight. In a dungeon where exact positoning is absolutely critical, then sacrificing damage for push is a good choice.<br>
<br>
What I'm talking about is losing damage for no reason at all. <br>
<br>
Oh yeh, all pets should be parked together, preferably whichever way is most convenient for the puller. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=h0gfather>H0gfather</A> at: 11/30/02 4:13:11 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=varaho1>Varaho1</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_fire.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>will kick your @$$</span><br>  Posts: 1136<br> <font color=#FF0000>(11/30/02 4:16:25 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthearena.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2557.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Pets, Positioning, and PoP.</span><hr size=1> I have come to find out the average tank does not read these boards, although we tend to get quite a bit of the abnormal ones. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mikar>Mikar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 40<br> <font color=#FF0000>(11/30/02 4:22:57 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthearena.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2557.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Pets, Positioning, and PoP.</span><hr size=1> As a cleric this is one of the points where I can tell a great tank from an average one. <br>
