<br>
What used to work really well for my groups was if the mage would /pet guard the pet AWAY from where we fought, then I would manipulate the mob where I wanted it and then the mage sent in pet. Oftentimes, it's very hard to pull aggro off a backstabbing 61+ waterpet, so when that is first engaged you have to either fight where it is, or let the pet die when you try and position mob.<br>
<br>
On the other hand, I've been grouping with a mage that insists on pulling (and does a splendid job, actually) working with the cleric, enchanter or druid/ranger in group to pacify/harmonize the mobs and then pulling them with malosini and kiting them around till the mob in camp enrages, which is when I'll switch targets to the new one and start beating that up.<br>
<br>
I know you play on Trib, Hogfather, but never had the pleasure of grouping with you I think <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   - but do me a favor and don't let the MT pull as well, you lose far far more damage from melee PCs over the course of an evening by not having auto attack on for the melee in group while mobs are getting pulled than you lose the marginal dps between water pet and, say, epic pet. I know I personally lose ~100dps whenever a mob is not in camp, which is partly why I don't like pulling myself, it's inefficient - even a mage with Velk boots pulling would put the aggregate damage up compared to me pulling. <p><big><center><b><a href=http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=19405 target=blank>Marshall Sscaley Iceblade</a><br><i><a href=http://companions.windsofstorm.net>The Companions ~ Team Headstart</a></i> <br>
