<br>
One example of what I mean, I pull a mob to camp.  I position it with a nice open back for the pets and the Rogues.  Then wham, the shammy casts slow from about a mile away and as high up on the wall as possible.  Suddenly I have a mob at the top of the wall beating the shaman's brains out.  I rush up there only to find I have a hard time even making contact because the pets have followed it up the wall.  And even once I do reaquire agro I have no chance of pulling it down into a better position with an open back if no one will call their damn pets off.<br>
<br>
Partly this is a Shaman's problem, the slow should be cast when standing almost next to the MT since its almost inevitable it will generate agro.  An alternative would be to have someone root the mob before casting slow.  Either way, suddenly the mob is out of position and the pets are just adding to the problem, not solving it.<br>
<br>
It requires team work and an understanding of what needs to be accomplished for these situations to work out right.  And heaven forbid you should try and make a helpful suggestion, people take it like a mortal insult.  Like, these mobs run and we have a Ranger for snare, why use an earth pet and cause us to take more damage when they root the mob?<br>
<br>
You'll very rarely find the best coordination in a pick up group.<br>
